views: The Kantian thing-in-itself is not denied but relocated as a temporal aspect of our experience. Hegel's linguistic idealism is understood in terms of his realistic view of sensation. Instead of claiming that Kant's categorical imperative is too empty to provide concrete moral guidance, Hegel praises its emptiness as the foundation for a diverse society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aAnalysis (Philosophy). 0aEthics, Modern. 0aPhilosophy, Germanx19th century. 0aPhilosophy, Germany19th century. 4aHegel. 4aKant. 4acategorical imperative. 4aepistemology. 4aethical theory. 4aethics. 4aimmanence. 4alinguistic idealism. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804788533zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804788533423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804788533.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles